    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the load balancer looks okay but the reset happens so randomly. i've checked the target group health and it's not showing much. could it be something related to the connection idle timeout or maybe some kind of packet loss at the VPC level? it feels like something is just cutting the line out of nowhere.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Random resets during peak times, even when the load balancer *looks* fine, are classic signs of network congestion or a poorly configured timeout. It's a very common issue, and you've hit on some good suspects.\n\nFirst, check the **idle timeout** settings on both your load balancer and your EC2 instances. If the connection sits idle for too long, one of the endpoints might decide to drop it, thinking it's dead. You might also want to look into the **network throughput** metrics for the VPC itself. If the VPC is hitting its bandwidth ceiling, you'll see packet loss, and that's a prime candidate for a \"connection reset.\"",
      "source": "target",
