    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah i'll look into the idle timeouts. it's just so frustrating because it's such a weird, jittery error. it's like there's some ghost in the machine or something causing these sudden little glitches that don't show up in the standard metrics properly. any idea why it would behave so erratically like that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Erratic behavior, like a jittery glitch, is often the hallmark of a resource bottleneck or a race condition, which is exactly what happens when you have a lot of unpredictable, fast-moving traffic. It's like a swarm of tiny, disorganized things trying to squeeze through a narrow tunnel—a real mess!\n\nSometimes, this \"ghost in the machine\" isn't a malicious entity, but rather the operating system or the network stack itself getting overloaded. Think about the EC2 instance. If it's maxing out its CPU or memory during peak traffic, it might start dropping packets or delaying responses just long enough for the other side to time out and send that \"connection reset.\" A slow server is just as bad as a broken pipe, even if the pipe itself is physically fine.",
      "source": "target",
